From: Hefesto DualSense4Unix Project <hefesto-dualsense4unix@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Wed, 22 Jul 2026 21:00:00 -0300
Subject: [PATCH] input: keep the bond on Virtual Cable Unplug (HID power-off)

Since 5.85 moved BR/EDR HID input to the userspace HID (uhid) path, the HID
control-channel message VIRTUAL_CABLE_UNPLUG now reaches bluetoothd's input
profile and triggers device_remove_bonding(), deleting the on-disk bond from
/var/lib/bluetooth. Under the in-kernel hidp path (<= 5.72) the kernel absorbed
this message and the bond was never removed.

Some HID game controllers send Virtual Cable Unplug simply when they power off
or lose the radio link -- measured live on a Nintendo Switch Pro Controller
(bus 0005:057E:2009) and an 8BitDo in Switch mode: every power-off or
under-load disconnect evaporates the on-disk bond, forcing a full re-pair
before the controller can connect again. Devices that do not emit the message
(e.g. Sony DualSense) keep their bond and reconnect fine, which is why the
failure is controller-specific.

Keep the bond by default; set BLUEZ_HID_UNPLUG_REMOVES_BOND=1 in the service
environment to restore the historical (stock) behaviour. Everything else about
the unplug path (tearing down the uhid node, clearing the flag) is unchanged.

Signed-off-by: Hefesto DualSense4Unix Project <hefesto-dualsense4unix@users.noreply.github.com>
---
 profiles/input/device.c | 15 ++++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 14 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

--- a/profiles/input/device.c
+++ b/profiles/input/device.c
@@ -172,8 +172,21 @@ static void input_device_free(struct input_device *idev)

 static void virtual_cable_unplug(struct input_device *idev)
 {
-	device_remove_bonding(idev->device,
+	/*
+	 * HEFESTO BOND-KEEP-01: a HID device that emits Virtual Cable Unplug
+	 * on power-off / link loss (measured: Nintendo Switch Pro Controller
+	 * and 8BitDo in Switch mode) would otherwise have its persistent bond
+	 * deleted here -- a uhid-path regression since 5.85 that forces a full
+	 * re-pair after every power-off. Keep the bond by default; set
+	 * BLUEZ_HID_UNPLUG_REMOVES_BOND=1 to restore the stock behaviour.
+	 */
+	const char *env = getenv("BLUEZ_HID_UNPLUG_REMOVES_BOND");
+
+	if (env && env[0] == '1')
+		device_remove_bonding(idev->device,
 				btd_device_get_bdaddr_type(idev->device));
+	else
+		DBG("keeping bond on virtual cable unplug (HEFESTO BOND-KEEP-01)");

 	idev->virtual_cable_unplug = false;
 }
